43
00:03:19,484 --> 00:03:23,327
So what do I mean by emergent tragedies and what does that have to do with the Shrouded Isle?

44
00:03:23,327 --> 00:03:25,328
It goes back to the game jam.

45
00:03:25,328 --> 00:03:28,090
The theme was, you are the monster.

46
00:03:28,090 --> 00:03:32,854
And instead of making a game about a physical monster, we wanted to explore why someone

47
00:03:32,854 --> 00:03:34,135
makes monstrous choices.

48
00:03:34,135 --> 00:03:40,380
Why does the leader of a community take actions that clearly harm members of that community?

49
00:03:41,337 --> 00:03:44,880
And in tackling that theme, we wanted to maintain ludonarrative congruence,

50
00:03:44,880 --> 00:03:48,824
which is to say that the narrative is told through the gameplay.

51
00:03:48,824 --> 00:03:51,446
But you might be more familiar with the more common term,

52
00:03:51,446 --> 00:03:55,791
ludonarrative dissonance, in which the narrative is undermined by the mechanics.

53
00:03:56,986 --> 00:04:03,068
So our creative goals were difficult to achieve because we needed to depict this dystopian society of the cults.

54
00:04:03,068 --> 00:04:08,769
But a lot of the design references we could find had this underlying utopian or heroic assumptions

55
00:04:08,769 --> 00:04:13,891
and had the risk of undermining the tragic narrative that we wanted to tell.

56
00:04:13,891 --> 00:04:22,553
To give a quick comparison, we wanted to depict a stagnant society that tries to control and constrain its people.

57
00:04:23,274 --> 00:04:29,720
By contrast, utopian games tend to focus on growth through the empowerment of a protagonist or the expansion of a community.

58
00:04:29,720 --> 00:04:33,764
We wanted to explore the divisions within the cult.

59
00:04:33,764 --> 00:04:35,846
What political games are being played?

60
00:04:35,846 --> 00:04:38,668
Who is seen as virtuous or sinful?

61
00:04:38,668 --> 00:04:42,472
But most games we found depicted unity or assumed unity instead,

62
00:04:42,472 --> 00:04:46,355
whether it's a band of adventurers or an army that's loyal to a greater cause.

63
00:04:47,554 --> 00:04:51,138
Most importantly, though, we wanted the gameplay to depict failure.

64
00:04:51,138 --> 00:04:56,645
Telling a story about a corrupt society in which the leaders do whatever it takes to

65
00:04:56,645 --> 00:04:57,946
maintain their regime.

66
00:04:57,946 --> 00:05:04,894
But the majority of examples we found had an underlying message of triumph.

67
00:05:04,894 --> 00:05:08,558
Depicting victory over an evil foe or prosperity of a community.

68
00:05:10,602 --> 00:05:12,383
So why make emergent tragedies?

69
00:05:12,383 --> 00:05:15,905
Because it allows us to depict dystopias and moral grayness

70
00:05:15,905 --> 00:05:18,806
while achieving ludonarrative congruence.

71
00:05:18,806 --> 00:05:21,748
The narrative is told through the gameplay.

72
00:05:21,748 --> 00:05:23,849
We can make more impactful experiences

73
00:05:23,849 --> 00:05:26,410
than scripted content because the player becomes

74
00:05:26,410 --> 00:05:28,892
an active participant and thereby causes

75
00:05:28,892 --> 00:05:31,513
their own downfall, or in rare cases,

76
00:05:31,513 --> 00:05:33,314
succeeds at an immense cost.

77
00:05:34,649 --> 00:05:36,190
But doing this is very challenging,

78
00:05:36,190 --> 00:05:38,671
because we have to find alternative gameplay elements

79
00:05:38,671 --> 00:05:41,032
to replace key aspects of utopian design.

80
00:05:41,032 --> 00:05:45,093
So this talk will be analyzing three gameplay elements

81
00:05:45,093 --> 00:05:47,714
that were used in the Shrouded Isle

82
00:05:47,714 --> 00:05:49,375
to create emergent tragedies.

83
00:05:49,375 --> 00:05:51,816
So first we'll look at how physical resources

84
00:05:51,816 --> 00:05:54,737
were replaced entirely with psychological resources.

85
00:05:54,737 --> 00:05:56,958
Then we'll talk about the core gameplay,

86
00:05:56,958 --> 00:05:58,999
examining how process-oriented mechanics

87
00:05:58,999 --> 00:06:01,880
were replaced with character-oriented mechanics.

88
00:06:02,482 --> 00:06:04,404
Finally, we'll talk about progression systems.

89
00:06:04,404 --> 00:06:07,086
Spatial expansion or tech upgrades

90
00:06:07,086 --> 00:06:08,888
were substituted with progression

91
00:06:08,888 --> 00:06:10,430
through information gathering.

92
00:06:10,430 --> 00:06:12,832
So let's first talk about resources.

93
00:06:12,832 --> 00:06:16,735
In the Game Jam version, two of the town's resources

94
00:06:16,735 --> 00:06:18,377
were physical, food and shelter.

95
00:06:18,377 --> 00:06:21,359
This was a sensible need for the town,

96
00:06:21,359 --> 00:06:23,682
but it was too easy for the player to stock up

97
00:06:23,682 --> 00:06:26,664
and fill the bar and imply a state of prosperity

98
00:06:26,664 --> 00:06:27,165
for the town.

99
00:06:28,066 --> 00:06:32,808
And we could have balanced the resource management to make the state of prosperity difficult to achieve,

100
00:06:32,808 --> 00:06:39,570
but there was a deeper problem in that directly managing food and shelter really felt irrelevant to a cult leader's interests.

101
00:06:39,570 --> 00:06:46,293
So in the final release, we replaced all physical resources with psychological resources.

102
00:06:46,293 --> 00:06:51,855
This way, the core economy of the game revolves around what a cult leader would care about, faith and politics.

103
00:06:53,323 --> 00:06:56,504
So in the bottom row there, you see the five virtues of the cult.

104
00:06:56,504 --> 00:07:00,325
Ignorance, fervor, discipline, penitence, and obedience.

105
00:07:00,325 --> 00:07:05,266
These variables are affected by the actions and traits of the townspeople.

106
00:07:05,266 --> 00:07:07,387
If characters behave virtuously, the bars go up.

107
00:07:07,387 --> 00:07:10,188
If they behave sinfully, the bars go down.

108
00:07:10,188 --> 00:07:13,328
If the bar slips below the threshold for too long,

109
00:07:13,328 --> 00:07:15,809
the people lose faith in the cult and the game ends.

110
00:07:17,519 --> 00:07:19,760
The upper row holds the political resources,

111
00:07:19,760 --> 00:07:23,281
the opinions of the five great houses of the village.

112
00:07:23,281 --> 00:07:25,662
So on the far left, you'll see that House Kegney

113
00:07:25,662 --> 00:07:28,323
feels satisfied with the regime,

114
00:07:28,323 --> 00:07:30,943
while neighboring House Iosefka in the second column

115
00:07:30,943 --> 00:07:32,444
feels merely neutral.

116
00:07:32,444 --> 00:07:35,185
When you bestow favor on a house

117
00:07:35,185 --> 00:07:36,865
by using their members as advisors,

118
00:07:36,865 --> 00:07:39,726
their opinions go up and their opinion goes down

119
00:07:39,726 --> 00:07:42,867
when you exclude them or kill members of their family

120
00:07:42,867 --> 00:07:44,428
for this seasonal sacrifice.

121
00:07:45,818 --> 00:07:47,839
If any has his opinion drops too low for too long,

122
00:07:47,839 --> 00:07:50,020
they revolt and the game ends.

123
00:07:50,020 --> 00:07:54,242
So the big benefit of using psychological resources

124
00:07:54,242 --> 00:07:56,923
is that the player embraces the values

125
00:07:56,923 --> 00:07:57,743
of the cult implicitly.

126
00:07:57,743 --> 00:08:01,925
Even if the player personally disagrees in the real world

127
00:08:01,925 --> 00:08:03,505
that raising ignorance is a good thing,

128
00:08:03,505 --> 00:08:06,406
they quickly learn that it is absolutely necessary

129
00:08:06,406 --> 00:08:08,287
for their cult to survive in the game.

130
00:08:08,287 --> 00:08:10,548
Furthermore, they are

131
00:08:11,577 --> 00:08:17,805
The psychological resources are divorced from objective reality or survival of the townspeople.

132
00:08:17,805 --> 00:08:22,510
So as a result, the player's narrative interests are dissociated from the villager's narrative

133
00:08:22,510 --> 00:08:28,578
interests, which motivates the players to make rather Machiavellian decisions when difficult

134
00:08:28,578 --> 00:08:29,359
situations arise.

135
00:08:31,425 --> 00:08:35,367
There's a further benefit in that you can keep the game in a state of volatile stagnation.

136
00:08:35,367 --> 00:08:39,909
As opposed to having an economy that just keeps growing and growing and growing over

137
00:08:39,909 --> 00:08:44,591
the course of a playthrough, the overall size remains relatively stagnant or even in slight

138
00:08:44,591 --> 00:08:45,832
decline.

139
00:08:45,832 --> 00:08:51,535
So, at the same time, the individual resources have high volatility so that the crises in

140
00:08:51,535 --> 00:08:53,135
the game emerge dynamically.

141
00:08:54,176 --> 00:08:55,457
So let me give you a quick example.

142
00:08:55,457 --> 00:08:57,739
I'm going to select Chessa on the very far left

143
00:08:57,739 --> 00:09:01,863
of the advisors list as my lead advisor this season.

144
00:09:01,863 --> 00:09:03,824
She belongs to House Kegney,

145
00:09:03,824 --> 00:09:05,926
so she specializes in burning books.

146
00:09:05,926 --> 00:09:08,789
If she succeeds, she'll raise ignorance

147
00:09:08,789 --> 00:09:10,030
by a moderate amount this month.

148
00:09:10,030 --> 00:09:13,473
She's also personally a sadist,

149
00:09:13,473 --> 00:09:16,595
so she'll raise fervor significantly by her example.

150
00:09:16,595 --> 00:09:18,817
This is really great because fervor

151
00:09:18,817 --> 00:09:20,198
is dangerously low right now.

152
00:09:21,719 --> 00:09:26,581
She is also rebellious, which is a major vice.

153
00:09:26,581 --> 00:09:28,001
By using her as an advisor,

154
00:09:28,001 --> 00:09:31,442
her example will reduce obedience of the town

155
00:09:31,442 --> 00:09:32,303
below the critical threshold,

156
00:09:32,303 --> 00:09:36,284
and therefore create an overall disobedience problem

157
00:09:36,284 --> 00:09:37,144
for the village.

158
00:09:37,144 --> 00:09:39,805
In terms of politics,

159
00:09:39,805 --> 00:09:43,046
House Kegney will understandably be very happy

160
00:09:43,046 --> 00:09:45,227
that you entrusted Chesa to lead the town,

161
00:09:45,227 --> 00:09:47,668
and they become zealous supporters of your regime.

162
00:09:49,209 --> 00:09:56,277
In exchange, every other house is somewhat insulted and envious and counterbalances the economy.

163
00:09:56,277 --> 00:10:07,289
In the Epherson's case, it pushes them down just enough so that it breaks their camel's back, so to speak, and they will rebel next season.

164
00:10:07,289 --> 00:10:10,213
So maybe choosing Chesa isn't the best option right now.

165
00:10:12,158 --> 00:10:21,281
As we saw with the example, a simple choice of who should lead the town for a month was given a complex nuance because of the volatility of the individual variables.

166
00:10:21,281 --> 00:10:26,162
Each gain is counterbalanced by a comparable loss in other variables.

167
00:10:26,162 --> 00:10:36,324
So while having the high volatility for the individual variables, we avoid having a spiraling growth or collapse, which would unbalance the gameplay and also undermine the narrative.

168
00:10:37,799 --> 00:10:47,202
And we theoretically could have done this with physical resources, but I find that psychological resources are far easier to justify as having this volatility that I needed.

169
00:10:47,202 --> 00:10:55,705
Because it's easier to explain that Chessa is a fervent person who sometimes goes too far and tends to be disobedient and rebellious,

170
00:10:55,705 --> 00:11:02,067
rather than trying to justify why gathering food would result in destruction of shelters or decay of shelters.

171
00:11:04,505 --> 00:11:07,887
Reigns is a game that uses psychological resources to depict tragic outcomes.

172
00:11:07,887 --> 00:11:13,611
The resources in the game simultaneously represent the physical amount of something as well as

173
00:11:13,611 --> 00:11:14,852
the faction's strength.

174
00:11:14,852 --> 00:11:20,376
So, for example, the sword represents the physical size of your army as well as their

175
00:11:20,376 --> 00:11:23,057
relative political influence within your kingdom.

176
00:11:23,057 --> 00:11:28,861
If the bar is empty, your kingdom can't defend itself and becomes conquered by an invader.

177
00:11:28,861 --> 00:11:32,484
If the bar is too full, your general overthrows you in a coup d'etat.

178
00:11:33,412 --> 00:11:37,615
This careful balancing act combined with the volatile outcomes creates cascading crises.

179
00:11:37,615 --> 00:11:43,039
But at the same time, their economy is very fragile and strategic play is difficult without

180
00:11:43,039 --> 00:11:44,500
memorizing the card outcomes.

181
00:11:44,500 --> 00:11:50,825
So at some level, I do find that this undermines the player ownership of choices, but it works

182
00:11:50,825 --> 00:11:55,668
fine for Reigns because it embraces death with a whimsical tone and has a dynastic meta

183
00:11:55,668 --> 00:11:56,549
progression system.

184
00:11:56,549 --> 00:11:58,891
So even if you die, you get something in the end.

185
00:12:00,985 --> 00:12:05,247
Moving on, let's talk about character-oriented mechanics.

186
00:12:05,247 --> 00:12:08,949
Utopian simulations tend to have process-oriented mechanics.

187
00:12:08,949 --> 00:12:10,889
Critical actions or systems in the game

188
00:12:10,889 --> 00:12:13,170
are abstracted industrial processes

189
00:12:13,170 --> 00:12:15,591
or are done through an organization.

190
00:12:15,591 --> 00:12:17,492
A residential zone is drawn.

191
00:12:17,492 --> 00:12:19,493
Income is received every month.

192
00:12:19,493 --> 00:12:22,074
A research project is chosen and just completes over time.

193
00:12:22,074 --> 00:12:24,055
Even when characters are involved,

194
00:12:24,055 --> 00:12:27,456
they are largely interchangeable and only matter

195
00:12:27,456 --> 00:12:29,977
as far as how quickly they gather something or speed up

196
00:12:29,977 --> 00:12:30,697
the process.

197
00:12:32,086 --> 00:12:34,227
So going back to the Game Jam version for a second,

198
00:12:34,227 --> 00:12:37,748
at the time we also had a very process-oriented game.

199
00:12:37,748 --> 00:12:40,348
The player gave orders at the house level,

200
00:12:40,348 --> 00:12:42,749
so like house Kegney would gather food

201
00:12:42,749 --> 00:12:45,770
or house Josefka would build shelters and so forth.

202
00:12:45,770 --> 00:12:48,110
And the results were calculated in aggregate

203
00:12:48,110 --> 00:12:50,571
because it really didn't matter how each house

204
00:12:50,571 --> 00:12:51,992
gathered a particular resource.

205
00:12:53,103 --> 00:12:58,926
This felt dissatisfying because similar to what we were talking about with the psychological

206
00:12:58,926 --> 00:13:04,489
resources earlier, it didn't seem like what a cult leader would want to do or care about.

207
00:13:04,489 --> 00:13:09,072
We wanted the player to engage with individual characters, judging for themselves whether

208
00:13:09,072 --> 00:13:12,033
a villager is virtuous or sinful.

209
00:13:12,033 --> 00:13:15,575
We wanted the player to have a reason to want to sacrifice somebody.

210
00:13:17,325 --> 00:13:20,686
So we changed the mechanic to be entirely character-oriented instead.

211
00:13:20,686 --> 00:13:26,570
The goal was to dramatize resource management by having the player act through or act upon

212
00:13:26,570 --> 00:13:31,052
characters whose behavior was fundamentally unpredictable.

213
00:13:31,052 --> 00:13:35,514
While the player can order characters to do something, they can't fully control what they

214
00:13:35,514 --> 00:13:37,175
do or what the outcome will be.

215
00:13:37,175 --> 00:13:39,777
So let's go back to Chessa again.

216
00:13:39,777 --> 00:13:43,619
So in this playthrough, I don't really know her very well, but I'm still going to select

217
00:13:43,619 --> 00:13:45,500
her as a representative for House Keg.

218
00:13:46,201 --> 00:13:50,153
I'm going to need her help desperately this season because ignorance is at a critical

219
00:13:50,153 --> 00:13:53,843
level and members of House Kegney are responsible for raising it.

220
00:13:56,953 --> 00:14:01,076
As I don't know her very well, it's going to be hard to predict how she will impact the town.

221
00:14:01,076 --> 00:14:06,920
We know that because she's part of the Cagney family, she will most likely raise ignorance.

222
00:14:06,920 --> 00:14:09,001
But we don't know how severe her vice is.

223
00:14:09,001 --> 00:14:13,204
According to rumors, as you can see on the second tray under her name,

224
00:14:13,204 --> 00:14:15,025
she is rumored to be disobedient.

225
00:14:15,025 --> 00:14:18,367
So I'm just going to trust for now that it's not too serious.

226
00:14:18,367 --> 00:14:21,910
Unfortunately, Chessa screws up.

227
00:14:23,317 --> 00:14:29,921
She fails to find enough books to burn, and instead of raising ignorance, she actually reduces it instead.

228
00:14:29,921 --> 00:14:32,002
Not only that, her vice might be severe.

229
00:14:32,002 --> 00:14:37,166
We don't know exactly what she did, but she completely reduced the town's obedience.

230
00:14:37,166 --> 00:14:42,329
This is an infuriating outcome, because not only did she fail at what I trusted her to do,

231
00:14:42,329 --> 00:14:45,951
she turns out to be a terrible sinner who is misleading my people.

232
00:14:48,011 --> 00:14:53,254
I trusted Chessa because as the player, I was engaged with her at every single step.

233
00:14:53,254 --> 00:14:57,116
I personally appointed her, and then I personally ordered her to burn books.

234
00:14:57,116 --> 00:15:01,979
Due to the stress, I had a certain expectation of her, which she did not fulfill.

235
00:15:01,979 --> 00:15:04,640
I felt betrayed by her because...

236
00:15:06,323 --> 00:15:08,725
She was an individual that did this,

237
00:15:08,725 --> 00:15:10,946
and she was personally connected to me

238
00:15:10,946 --> 00:15:13,307
as a result of my orders to her.

239
00:15:13,307 --> 00:15:16,309
If an industrial process or an organization

240
00:15:16,309 --> 00:15:17,349
resulted in this outcome,

241
00:15:17,349 --> 00:15:19,250
I would only have myself to blame.

242
00:15:19,250 --> 00:15:21,771
But due to having character-oriented mechanics,

243
00:15:21,771 --> 00:15:24,213
we added dramatic context to what would otherwise

244
00:15:24,213 --> 00:15:26,794
be a really banal resource acquisition action.

245
00:15:29,037 --> 00:15:32,781
Another game that uses character-oriented mechanics to tell emergent narratives about

246
00:15:32,781 --> 00:15:36,144
expectations and betrayal is, of course, Darkest Dungeon.

247
00:15:36,144 --> 00:15:40,608
The player sends parties of adventurers down to these deadly crypts, and for the most part,

248
00:15:40,608 --> 00:15:42,470
the characters will obey the player's orders.

249
00:15:43,347 --> 00:15:48,031
However, as their stress rises from all the horrors that they encounter,

250
00:15:48,031 --> 00:15:55,717
the party gains afflictions, which are negative traits that permanently change how the character behaves.

251
00:15:55,717 --> 00:16:00,500
So, for example, being hopeless not only causes debuffs to the character,

252
00:16:00,500 --> 00:16:02,962
it causes the character to ignore the player's orders.

253
00:16:02,962 --> 00:16:07,405
Having one character with an affliction is manageable, but...

254
00:16:08,326 --> 00:16:12,211
it snowballs very quickly and eventually unless you pull out,

255
00:16:12,211 --> 00:16:14,734
the entire party will be full of afflictions.

256
00:16:14,734 --> 00:16:21,122
One thing that Darkest Dungeon does well is counterbalancing this,

257
00:16:21,122 --> 00:16:25,508
subverting this with the mechanic of virtues.

258
00:16:25,508 --> 00:16:25,648
So.

259
00:16:26,369 --> 00:16:29,552
There's a small chance that instead of gaining an affliction,

260
00:16:29,552 --> 00:16:33,056
you gain a positive trait which boosts the party instead.

261
00:16:33,056 --> 00:16:34,637
So for instance, being courageous

262
00:16:34,637 --> 00:16:36,599
as opposed to being hopeless.

263
00:16:36,599 --> 00:16:38,741
By doing so, the game subverts the player's

264
00:16:38,741 --> 00:16:40,863
negative expectation in a positive way,

265
00:16:40,863 --> 00:16:44,267
creating emergent narratives of heroism and turnabout.

266
00:16:44,267 --> 00:16:49,212
Moving on, let's talk about progression systems.

267
00:16:51,573 --> 00:16:53,313
We looked at two conventional approaches,

268
00:16:53,313 --> 00:16:55,174
which would have been to go wide

269
00:16:55,174 --> 00:16:58,815
and allow for spatial expansion

270
00:16:58,815 --> 00:17:00,235
and go tall and allow for upgrades.

271
00:17:00,235 --> 00:17:02,196
But thinking about it,

272
00:17:02,196 --> 00:17:04,536
it felt incompatible with the narrative

273
00:17:04,536 --> 00:17:07,877
because the island is isolated from the world

274
00:17:07,877 --> 00:17:11,278
and has a dwindling population due to ritual sacrifices.

275
00:17:11,278 --> 00:17:13,659
To have a progression system

276
00:17:13,659 --> 00:17:16,279
without having the cult grow in any way,

277
00:17:16,279 --> 00:17:18,220
we decided to use information.

278
00:17:19,728 --> 00:17:23,151
The way it works is through the townspeople and their traits.

279
00:17:23,151 --> 00:17:24,772
So let's take Bogdan here for an example.

280
00:17:24,772 --> 00:17:26,594
At the start of the playthrough,

281
00:17:26,594 --> 00:17:29,737
we might not know anything about Bogdan's behavior.

282
00:17:29,737 --> 00:17:32,620
But as the cult leader, the player has the right

283
00:17:32,620 --> 00:17:34,461
to investigate, excuse me,

284
00:17:34,461 --> 00:17:37,905
investigate members of their village for their behavior.

285
00:17:37,905 --> 00:17:40,507
So if we inquire about Bogdan's virtue,

286
00:17:40,507 --> 00:17:43,129
at the next stage, we understand

287
00:17:43,129 --> 00:17:45,372
that he's rumored to be obedient.

288
00:17:46,366 --> 00:17:51,110
But we still don't know exactly how much he will affect the town's obedience until we

289
00:17:51,110 --> 00:17:56,595
inquire about him again, and then it's revealed that he is timid, and we'll add five points

290
00:17:56,595 --> 00:17:58,036
of obedience every season.

291
00:17:58,036 --> 00:18:02,660
Through revealing traits, the player is given subjective rewards.

292
00:18:02,660 --> 00:18:05,042
The characters themselves do not change at all.

293
00:18:05,042 --> 00:18:08,505
They behave exactly the same, no matter how much their trait has been revealed.

294
00:18:08,505 --> 00:18:12,348
Instead, the player's perception of that character changes.

295
00:18:12,728 --> 00:18:16,329
Since the player can more accurately predict the character's impact,

296
00:18:16,329 --> 00:18:19,069
they can make better decisions as they reveal more traits.

297
00:18:19,069 --> 00:18:24,390
There's also a change in the villager's perception of that character in the final phase.

298
00:18:24,390 --> 00:18:29,651
So if the player unveils the fullest extent of a character's virtue or vice,

299
00:18:29,651 --> 00:18:34,152
it changes the bonuses and penalties in the sacrifice phase.

300
00:18:34,152 --> 00:18:35,233
So let's go back to Chessa.

301
00:18:35,233 --> 00:18:38,633
She drained the town's obedience because of her vice,

302
00:18:38,633 --> 00:18:41,654
but we don't know exactly what that vice is yet.

303
00:18:43,107 --> 00:18:47,410
When we inquire about it, we discover that she is rebellious.

304
00:18:47,410 --> 00:18:48,631
This is a major vice.

305
00:18:48,631 --> 00:18:54,815
At the end of the season, we have to choose one of the five advisors to sacrifice.

306
00:18:54,815 --> 00:18:57,556
And I'm going to make an example out of Chessa.

307
00:18:57,556 --> 00:19:01,819
Because I've exposed that she is rebellious,

308
00:19:01,819 --> 00:19:05,522
I'm able to make her family grudgingly accept this final outcome.

309
00:19:06,508 --> 00:19:08,509
Furthermore, her village, sorry,

310
00:19:08,509 --> 00:19:11,270
her death will send a message to the village,

311
00:19:11,270 --> 00:19:17,832
restoring some of the lost obedience.

312
00:19:17,832 --> 00:19:19,752
With Chessa's death, justice is served

313
00:19:19,752 --> 00:19:23,253
and the villagers have learned a lesson.

314
00:19:23,253 --> 00:19:25,794
As you saw, the benefit of using information progression

315
00:19:25,794 --> 00:19:29,575
is that it allows us to temporarily blind the player.

316
00:19:29,575 --> 00:19:31,535
By giving access to incomplete information,

317
00:19:31,535 --> 00:19:33,416
we can create scenarios in which players'

318
00:19:33,416 --> 00:19:35,257
good intentions go terribly wrong.

319
00:19:36,230 --> 00:19:38,432
It's in the player's best interest to gain information,

320
00:19:38,432 --> 00:19:40,954
so therefore the player is motivated

321
00:19:40,954 --> 00:19:42,295
to get to know the characters,

322
00:19:42,295 --> 00:19:44,537
which adds support to the character-oriented mechanics

323
00:19:44,537 --> 00:19:46,379
that we talked about in the previous section.

324
00:19:46,379 --> 00:19:50,203
And granted, this approach can be frustrating

325
00:19:50,203 --> 00:19:53,226
if the situation is completely opaque or unreadable,

326
00:19:53,226 --> 00:19:56,348
but the gameplay remains fair

327
00:19:56,348 --> 00:19:58,751
as long as the player is given some information

328
00:19:58,751 --> 00:20:00,793
and has active means of acquiring more.

329
00:20:01,521 --> 00:20:05,604
In fact, I would say that the player is rewarded for being prudent and having foresight as

330
00:20:05,604 --> 00:20:11,809
long as they can make reasonable assumptions about the missing information.

331
00:20:11,809 --> 00:20:16,953
Probably the single best example of information progression is Return of the Aubrey Dinn.

332
00:20:16,953 --> 00:20:21,296
The player is trying to figure out the fate of the crew and passengers on the Aubrey Dinn

333
00:20:21,296 --> 00:20:24,359
by using a magic pocket watch to go back to the moment of their death.

334
00:20:25,197 --> 00:20:29,159
By carefully observing the snapshot flashbacks

335
00:20:29,159 --> 00:20:31,981
for what the characters say, what they do,

336
00:20:31,981 --> 00:20:34,743
and whom they associate with,

337
00:20:34,743 --> 00:20:39,146
the player slowly pieces together faces with names

338
00:20:39,146 --> 00:20:40,267
until the truth is revealed.

339
00:20:40,267 --> 00:20:42,949
The game discourages guessing

340
00:20:42,949 --> 00:20:47,732
by only confirming your answers in sets of three,

341
00:20:47,732 --> 00:20:49,253
and directly warning the player

342
00:20:49,253 --> 00:20:51,835
if not enough information has been found

343
00:20:51,835 --> 00:20:53,916
to be able to actually identify the character.

344
00:20:55,019 --> 00:20:57,140
All the same, an astute player is able

345
00:20:57,140 --> 00:21:00,101
to make reasonable predictions about a character's identity

346
00:21:00,101 --> 00:21:02,382
long before having enough evidence

347
00:21:02,382 --> 00:21:04,383
based on their appearance, occupation,

348
00:21:04,383 --> 00:21:07,585
and the language that they speak.

349
00:21:07,585 --> 00:21:10,186
So to bring this all together,

350
00:21:10,186 --> 00:21:12,527
emergent tragedies allow players

351
00:21:12,527 --> 00:21:14,748
to create their own downfall.

352
00:21:14,748 --> 00:21:18,169
We can tell narratives about dystopias and moral grayness,

353
00:21:18,169 --> 00:21:20,710
not through scripted content, but through gameplay itself.

354
00:21:22,990 --> 00:21:26,033
Psychological resources are the fundamental step in this,

355
00:21:26,033 --> 00:21:28,595
and that it encourages players to embrace

356
00:21:28,595 --> 00:21:32,199
alternative paradigms and discourage min-maxing.

357
00:21:32,199 --> 00:21:35,522
Even if the player personally does not agree

358
00:21:35,522 --> 00:21:37,524
with the values of the cult and the Shrouded Isle,

359
00:21:37,524 --> 00:21:39,926
they must implicitly accept them within the game

360
00:21:39,926 --> 00:21:44,570
